% I have run through the fields %

00:57.429 --> 01:01.766
% Only to be with you %

01:01.850 --> 01:06.562
% Only to be with you %

01:06.645 --> 01:11.941
% I have run, I have crawled %

01:12.025 --> 01:16.570
% I have scaled these city walls %

01:16.654 --> 01:21.074
% These city walls %

01:21.158 --> 01:25.745
% Only to be with you %

01:25.828 --> 01:31.041
% But I still haven't found %

01:31.083 --> 01:34.544
% What I'm looking for %

01:35.878 --> 01:40.048
% But I still haven't found %

01:40.090 --> 01:43.134
% What I'm looking for %

01:45.344 --> 01:47.304
[Man] Fisher, pick up.

01:47.388 --> 01:50.390
Fisher, it's me!
Fisher, pick up!

01:50.474 --> 01:53.685
I'm late, come on, come on.
I need to bounce some ideas off you.

01:53.768 --> 01:55.728
Mine are all boring,
done it, been there.

01:55.812 --> 01:56.854
Hey, Ike!

01:56.938 --> 02:00.107
When are you guys gonna stop
waking me up every morning?

02:00.190 --> 02:02.567
When your column stops
putting me to sleep.

02:02.651 --> 02:05.278
- Funny, funny.
- Yo, Jonah!

02:05.361 --> 02:07.405
Fisher, come on!
Are you really not there?

02:07.488 --> 02:09.615
All right, cool.
I'll talk to you later.

02:09.698 --> 02:12.659
Excuse me. I'm thinking of doing
an article about limousines.

02:12.742 --> 02:15.787
What do you think about people
who've never been in one?

02:15.828 --> 02:17.663
I don't know people like that.

02:17.747 --> 02:21.625
I need someone to bounce some ideas
off of and get the juices flowing.

02:21.667 --> 02:24.753
I got one hour,
27 minutes, 52 seconds.

02:24.836 --> 02:26.796
Hey, Ike! When are you gonna
put me in a column?

02:26.879 --> 02:29.757
- When your T-shirts stop shrinking.
- [Woman] Shrinks?

02:29.840 --> 02:32.718
-Funny. He's kidding. He's just kidding.
-Oh, forget it.

02:32.801 --> 02:36.012
- Here, give me $5. Give me $2.
- [Woman] No way.

02:36.095 --> 02:39.015
Folks, I got nice shirts here.
Look!

02:39.098 --> 02:41.308
"I love everybody. You're next."

02:41.392 --> 02:44.561
%[Female Singing]

02:56.029 --> 02:59.240
So what's in store for us
in tomorrow's column?

02:59.323 --> 03:02.034
[Groans]
I don't know yet.

03:03.076 --> 03:07.038
I'm, uh, kind of
a last-minute man.

03:07.080 --> 03:10.333
You know, till an hour or two
before deadline, I don't get any ideas.

03:12.001 --> 03:14.586
So you get your ideas
for your column from life.

03:14.669 --> 03:16.588
Start up a conversation with a woman
in a bar.

03:16.671 --> 03:19.340
Attack her dart playing
and try to get a rise out of her...

03:19.423 --> 03:23.010
while you contemplate whether
or not she's worth hitting on.

03:23.093 --> 03:25.804
No, I can't hit on you
till I get an idea.

03:25.887 --> 03:27.639
Wh-- That's flattering.

03:27.722 --> 03:30.057
[Ike]
No, you don't understand.

03:30.099 --> 03:33.602
I understand. See,
my not responding to you baiting me...

03:33.685 --> 03:37.397
will inspire one of those bitter
diatribes you like to write about women.

03:37.480 --> 03:39.774
[Ike]I don't write bitter diatribes
about women.

03:39.857 --> 03:42.651
- Oh-ho.
- Very often. I could.

03:42.735 --> 03:45.570
Only when the ideas
aren't flowing, huh?

03:45.612 --> 03:47.697
It's so nice to meet you,
one-minute man.

03:47.781 --> 03:50.741
It's last-minute man.

03:50.825 --> 03:52.993
Whatever.

03:53.077 --> 03:56.288
Want to hear something funny? For a
good-looking guy, you strike out a lot.

03:56.371 --> 03:59.415
- [Bartender] Have you noticed that?
- [Phone Ringing]

03:59.499 --> 04:01.834
- I bet it's your ex-wife.
- [Man] Excuse me.

04:01.917 --> 04:03.794
I've seen much worse.

04:03.877 --> 04:06.588
[Bartender]
No, Ike's not here.

04:06.671 --> 04:09.716
I say, I've seen much worse.

04:09.799 --> 04:12.301
- I'll tell him when he comes in.
- Excuse me?

04:12.385 --> 04:15.262
The brush-off.

04:15.304 --> 04:18.055
I've witnessed far more...

04:18.098 --> 04:21.184
treacherous and nefarious exits
than that.

04:22.310 --> 04:24.770
At least she castigated you
in private.

04:24.853 --> 04:28.356
Not as private as I thought.
Kevin, you got some napkins there?

04:28.440 --> 04:32.276
- Wiping or writing?
- I'll let you know.

04:32.318 --> 04:35.279
They love you.
They hate you.

04:35.321 --> 04:37.864
They're hot.
They're cold. They're high.

04:37.948 --> 04:39.908
They're up. They're down.

04:39.949 --> 04:43.577
This is fun making a list with you,
but I do have a column to write.

04:43.661 --> 04:45.454
Ike.

04:45.537 --> 04:49.541
But you have yet to find
a really superb idea.

04:49.624 --> 04:53.002
There's a girl from my hometown
that you could write about.

04:53.085 --> 04:55.004
Excuse me,
but we don't need any ideas.

04:55.087 --> 04:58.632
She likes to dump grooms at the altar.
They call her the "Runaway Bride."

04:58.715 --> 05:01.718
She's performed the travesty
seven or eight times.

05:01.801 --> 05:05.429
Turns around, runs like hell.
Bolts. Adios.

05:05.471 --> 05:08.140
Plows down the aisle,
knocking old ladies out of her way...

05:08.223 --> 05:11.017
Like the Running of the Bulls
in Pamplona.

05:11.101 --> 05:13.561
And guess what!
She's got the next victim all lined up.

05:13.644 --> 05:16.772
She's turning another body
on the spit.

05:16.855 --> 05:19.983
[Ike]
Okay, Italics, here we go.

05:22.402 --> 05:26.655
[Ike's Voice] Today is
a day of profound introspection.

05:26.739 --> 05:29.574
I have been accused
of using this column...

05:29.658 --> 05:33.786
to direct bitter diatribes
at the opposite sex.

05:33.870 --> 05:36.956
This uncomfortable accusation...

05:36.997 --> 05:41.209
has plunged me into at least 15 minutes
of serious reflection,

05:41.293 --> 05:43.378
from which I have emerged...

05:43.461 --> 05:48.757
with the conclusion that, yes,
I traffic in female stereotypes.

05:50.801 --> 05:54.303
"But how can one blame me when
every time I step out my front door,

05:54.345 --> 05:58.515
I meet fresh proof that the female
archetypes are alive and well."

05:58.599 --> 06:02.102
"The mother, the virgin,
the whore, the crone."

06:02.185 --> 06:05.063
"They're elbowing you in the subway,
stealing your cabs,

06:05.146 --> 06:07.815
and overwhelming you
with perfume in elevators."

06:07.898 --> 06:09.858
"But perhaps in fairness
to the fairer sex,

06:09.942 --> 06:14.112
I do need to broaden my horizon and add
some new goddesses to the pantheon."

06:14.195 --> 06:18.157
"I would like to nominate
for deity the cheerleader, the coed...

06:18.240 --> 06:21.243
and the man-eater, the last
of which concerns me most today."

06:21.326 --> 06:24.704
"In ancient Greece, this fearsome female
was known as Erinys,

06:24.746 --> 06:26.747
the devouring death goddess."

06:26.831 --> 06:28.499
"In India, she is Kali,

06:28.541 --> 06:31.043
who likes to devour
her boyfriend Shiva's entrails..."

06:31.126 --> 06:33.837
"while her yoni devours
his dot, dot, dot... never mind."

06:33.920 --> 06:38.966
"In Indonesia, the bloody-jawed man-eater
is called Ragma."

06:39.049 --> 06:42.427
You notice these are
all countries without cable.

06:42.511 --> 06:44.888
"And in Hale, Maryland,

06:44.929 --> 06:47.098
where she helps run
the family hardware store,

06:47.181 --> 06:51.852
she is known as Miss Maggie Carpenter,
a.k.a. the Runaway Bride."

06:51.935 --> 06:54.771
"What is unusual about
Miss Carpenter...

06:54.854 --> 06:59.316
is that she likes to dress her men up
as grooms before she devours them."

06:59.400 --> 07:04.237
One antique hot-water handle
with the "hot" still on it.

07:04.321 --> 07:07.073
Guaranteed to fit
any American Standard cast-iron tub...

07:07.156 --> 07:11.743
with a four-inch center mount
made between 1924 and 1938.

07:11.827 --> 07:13.870
In other words,
Mr. Paxton,

07:13.954 --> 07:15.997
I think you are out of the doghouse
with Mrs. Paxton.

07:16.080 --> 07:17.040
Hallelujah!

07:17.123 --> 07:18.833
I'll see you later.
I'll put it on your charge.

07:18.916 --> 07:23.253
There's a possibility
she hasn't seen this yet.

07:23.337 --> 07:27.257
Maybe she just hasn't picked up a paper.
Know what I mean?

07:27.298 --> 07:30.134
- Or not.
- [Man]Maggie?

07:30.217 --> 07:32.886
Earl, you don't need an air-conditioner.
You need an attic fan.

07:32.970 --> 07:36.014
There's more in the back. Hey.

07:39.183 --> 07:41.101
What?

07:41.185 --> 07:44.271
So, Mag,
you've seen this, huh?

07:44.354 --> 07:46.272
Yes, I've seen it.

07:47.190 --> 07:49.108
And it is the rudest,

07:49.192 --> 07:51.694
most offensive...

07:51.777 --> 07:55.072
joke anyone
has ever played on me!

07:55.113 --> 07:58.032
You guys, how long did this take you?
Where did you get it done?

07:58.116 --> 08:00.326
You're both creeps, by the way.
I should "disinvite" you.

08:00.409 --> 08:05.664
Maggie, you told us
no bachelorette jokes, so we didn't--

08:11.293 --> 08:14.755
Holy moly.

08:16.464 --> 08:19.550
- Bag. Bag!
- She's going. She's gonna go!

08:19.634 --> 08:23.345
Here's the bag. Breathe!

08:23.429 --> 08:26.098
[Female Singer]
% Ready, ready, ready, ready %

08:26.181 --> 08:28.266
% Ready to run %

08:28.349 --> 08:31.727
% All I'm ready to do is have some fun %

08:31.811 --> 08:33.270
[Barks]

08:33.354 --> 08:39.609
% What's all this talk about love %

08:39.650 --> 08:42.193
[Grunting]

08:44.154 --> 08:47.115
[Radio] On the local front,
our town of Hale, Maryland,

08:47.199 --> 08:49.659
is still buzzing about
the less-than-flattering article...

08:49.742 --> 08:52.370
about their native daughter,
Maggie Carpenter.

08:52.453 --> 08:54.538
Her bridal exploits were taken
to task...

08:54.622 --> 08:57.207
by New York columnist
Ike Graham in USA Today.

08:57.290 --> 08:59.376
- Mr. Graham called her--
- [Radio Off]

08:59.459 --> 09:02.920
[Maggie's Voice]
Dear Editor: Greetings from the sticks.

09:03.004 --> 09:06.965
Perhaps you believe that
a rural education is focused mainly...

09:07.007 --> 09:11.260
on hog calling and tractor maintenance
rather than reading.

09:11.344 --> 09:13.304
Why else would you print a piece
of fiction about me and call it fact?

09:13.304 --> 09:15.180
Why else would you print a piece
of fiction about me and call it fact?

09:18.350 --> 09:21.227
I suppose Mr. Graham was too busy
thinking up slanderous statements...

09:21.311 --> 09:23.312
about how I dump men for kicks...

09:23.354 --> 09:26.190
to bother with something silly
like accuracy in reporting.

09:26.273 --> 09:29.192
Which is understandable, because
with a man-eater like me on the loose,

09:29.276 --> 09:31.194
who has time to check facts?

09:31.277 --> 09:34.113
- Hey, Frances, lunch today?
- No, I'm going to the bank.

09:34.196 --> 09:36.115
- Sure?
- Sorry, Ike.

09:36.198 --> 09:39.409
- All right. Hey.
- Hey.

09:39.493 --> 09:41.619
I'm going to put in
a good word for you.

09:41.703 --> 09:42.829
Don't mention my name.

09:42.870 --> 09:44.872
[Maggie's Voice]
That's why I was surprised to find...

09:44.914 --> 09:47.207
Mr. Graham's editor was a woman.

09:47.291 --> 09:50.543
Call me a sentimental fool, but I hoped
we man-eaters could stick together.

09:50.585 --> 09:53.087
"Anyway, I'm just dropping
you big-city folk this little note...

09:53.171 --> 09:55.673
to say that I have thought
of a ritual sacrifice..."

09:55.714 --> 09:57.758
"that would satisfy
my current appetite:

09:57.841 --> 10:00.177
"Ike Graham's column
on a platter."

10:00.218 --> 10:02.512
"Yours truly, Maggie Carpenter.
P.S.

10:02.554 --> 10:06.182
"I have enclosed a list of gross factual
misrepresentations in your article.

10:06.265 --> 10:08.851
There are fifteen."

10:09.935 --> 10:11.895
[Ike]
Funny. I like her.

10:11.936 --> 10:14.522
She's got spunk.

10:14.605 --> 10:18.192
Ike, look. She sent us this list.
Our lawyers say it's actionable.

10:18.275 --> 10:20.360
[Sighs]

10:20.402 --> 10:22.779
I left you four messages.
You don't return my calls.

10:22.862 --> 10:25.740
I never returned your calls.
Even when we were married I didn't--

10:25.781 --> 10:30.619
-What's Fisher doing here?
-Ellie asked me to offer moral support.

10:30.702 --> 10:33.705
Since when does Ellie
need moral support?

10:33.746 --> 10:36.165
It's for you, Ike.

10:38.751 --> 10:40.711
What? What?

10:40.752 --> 10:42.879
Journalism lesson number one:

10:42.921 --> 10:46.048
If you fabricate your facts,
you get fired.

10:46.090 --> 10:49.551
Lesson number two:
Never work for your former spouse.

10:49.593 --> 10:54.222
That has nothing to do with it. You
cooked this story up, and you know it!

10:54.305 --> 10:56.307
I did not cook anything up.
I had a source.

10:56.390 --> 10:58.642
Someone reliable?
Some boozehound in a bar?

10:58.726 --> 11:00.144
In vino veritas.

11:00.227 --> 11:04.731
Hey, hey, hey. Don't knock drunk guys
in bars. It means they're not driving.

11:04.772 --> 11:06.732
Besides, lam a columnist.

11:06.774 --> 11:09.568
This is what columnists
are supposed to do.

11:09.610 --> 11:13.488
It's what you like. We push,
we stretch, we go out on a limb.

11:13.655 --> 11:15.198
That's what makes me good!

11:15.281 --> 11:18.617
No, that's what
makes you unemployed.

11:21.328 --> 11:24.414
All right. Let's consider
that my wrist has been slapped.

11:24.456 --> 11:27.458
There. Slap it.
Go ahead, just--

11:27.542 --> 11:30.127
Slap my wrist.
That's done.

11:30.210 --> 11:35.673
Just give me a call when you feel
that I've served my time, and move on.

11:38.426 --> 11:41.136
This is permanent, Ike.

11:42.721 --> 11:45.974
If you go quietly,
I'll get you severance pay.

11:55.565 --> 11:57.525
[Secretary]
I'm sorry, Ike.

11:59.485 --> 12:01.779
[Train Whistle Blowing]

12:03.780 --> 12:06.074
[Crossing Bell Ringing]

12:21.629 --> 12:25.507
- [Maggie]Bob? Honey?
- In the kitchen!

12:25.549 --> 12:27.509
Honey, she canned him! Honey?

12:27.550 --> 12:30.344
Bob, she canned him!

12:30.386 --> 12:33.389
- Yea! What are you talking about?
- Listen, it's in the paper.

12:33.472 --> 12:35.474
- Try this on first.
- Okay.

12:35.515 --> 12:37.892
I wanna read it to you,
so come over this way.

12:37.976 --> 12:40.186
Ready?
"Dear Maggie Carpenter:

12:40.269 --> 12:43.564
I apologize to you
for this unfortunate matter.''

12:43.647 --> 12:48.651
Here it is. "Ike Graham's column will
no longer be appearing in this paper.

12:48.735 --> 12:51.028
Best of luck
in your upcoming marriage."

12:51.070 --> 12:54.323
Okay, this is the weight of the pack
you'll be carrying in the Himalayas.

12:54.364 --> 12:58.326
- You let me know if it's too heavy.
- Okay. Whoa!

12:58.410 --> 13:02.371
A little... yeah. Yeah,
a little heavy, baby. [Laughing]

13:02.413 --> 13:04.706
[Screams, Laughs]

13:10.003 --> 13:13.130
[Phone Rings, Message Machine] Hi,
it's me. Leave a message after the beep.

13:13.214 --> 13:15.883
If you want to leave a fax,
buy me a fax machine.

13:15.924 --> 13:18.343
[Beeps]
Ike, Fisher.

13:18.385 --> 13:23.097
Get up. I can turn
this Runaway Bride story around.

13:23.180 --> 13:26.516
I'm doing a photo spread for G.Q.
today by the convey or belt.

13:26.558 --> 13:28.977
Meet me. I'll save your tush.

13:29.060 --> 13:32.438
And since I do freelance stuff
for G.Q. now, I have an idea.

13:32.521 --> 13:35.065
- What are you saying?
- Vindication.

13:35.149 --> 13:37.192
How would you like some?

13:37.234 --> 13:40.695
A chance to prove that although
your story wasn't entirely factual,

13:40.778 --> 13:43.364
your theory was correct.

13:43.447 --> 13:47.534
- The real story on Miss Carpenter.
- All the gory details.

13:47.617 --> 13:49.577
Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm.

13:49.619 --> 13:52.830
[Fisher] And if she runs again,
you got a cover story.

13:54.498 --> 13:57.084
[Male Singers]
% Oh, here she comes %

13:57.167 --> 13:59.544
% Watch out, boy
she'll chew you up %

13:59.586 --> 14:02.005
% Oh, here she comes %

14:02.088 --> 14:04.924
% She's a man-eater %

14:04.965 --> 14:07.926
% Oh, here she comes %

14:07.968 --> 14:10.553
% Watch out, boy
she'll chew you up %

14:10.595 --> 14:12.764
% Oh, here she comes %

14:12.847 --> 14:15.724
% She's a man-eater %

14:15.766 --> 14:18.310
% She'll only come out at night %

14:18.393 --> 14:21.312
% The lean and hungry type %

14:21.396 --> 14:25.066
% Nothing is new
I've seen her here before %

14:26.859 --> 14:29.486
% Watching and waiting %

14:29.569 --> 14:34.574
% She's seated with you
but here yes are on the door %

14:36.700 --> 14:39.578
% I wouldn't if I were you %

14:39.619 --> 14:42.580
% I know what she can do %

14:42.622 --> 14:48.168
%She's deadly, man
She could really rip your world apart %

14:48.252 --> 14:50.545
% Mind over matter %

14:50.629 --> 14:55.424
% Oh, the beauty is there
but a beast is in the heart %

14:55.466 --> 14:57.968
Here you go.
Right upstairs to the left.

14:58.010 --> 14:59.970
Thanks. How late's
the restaurant open?

15:00.012 --> 15:03.431
- 8:30 every night.
- [Chuckles] That late, huh?

15:12.439 --> 15:15.316
[Maggie]
Cindy, can you eighty-six Sprout?

15:15.358 --> 15:18.652
He's licking up all the petroleum
distillates I'm trying to put in.

15:18.736 --> 15:21.196
Oh, sorry.
She's an obedience school dropout.

15:21.279 --> 15:25.116
- [Sprout Barks]
- Have a seat.

15:25.158 --> 15:30.162
% [Barbershop Quartet Vocalizing] %

15:30.245 --> 15:32.289
[Applause]

15:32.372 --> 15:36.834
Thank you. We'll see you, ladies and
gentlemen, in the hotel on the weekend.

15:46.884 --> 15:49.261
You're a goddess.
You're a goddess!

15:49.345 --> 15:53.390
[Into Tape Recorder]
Shazam! I think I'm in Mayberry.

15:53.473 --> 15:56.684
[Maggie]I didn't have to change a
gasket, just put in new hydraulic fluid.

15:56.768 --> 15:59.311
[Woman] Stop it! When you talk like
that, it turns me on and frightens me.

15:59.395 --> 16:03.982
- Oh, you turn a girl's head.
- [Laughing] Whoa!

16:04.065 --> 16:07.402
Excuse me. Hello?

16:07.485 --> 16:09.695
Excuse me. Could you help--
I'm looking for Maggie Carpenter.

16:09.737 --> 16:14.241
There was a, uh, note on the door
of the hardware store across the street.

16:14.324 --> 16:16.367
- Are you a reporter?
- What?

16:16.451 --> 16:18.452
It's just been
our experience that...

16:18.536 --> 16:21.372
anyone who comes in here
with tassels on his loafers...

16:21.413 --> 16:26.084
is a big-city reporter
wanting to do an interview with Maggie.

16:26.167 --> 16:28.169
About her upcoming
wedding and all.

16:28.211 --> 16:33.340
Actually about her getting
that asshole from New York fired.

16:33.382 --> 16:38.261
I am just such a reporter.
And who are you?

16:38.344 --> 16:42.765
- Peggy Flemming. Not the ice skater.
- [Laughs]

16:42.848 --> 16:44.850
[Peggy]
Come in, come in.

16:44.933 --> 16:47.185
[Ike]
Who are these lovely ladies?

16:47.227 --> 16:50.229
Hi. I'm Cindy.
Maggie's unmarried cousin.

16:50.313 --> 16:53.023
Mrs. Pressman.
No relation. Oh, sorry.

16:53.065 --> 16:55.067
[Peggy]
And you are?

16:55.108 --> 16:58.403
Looking... for Maggie.

16:58.444 --> 17:01.113
Maggie, someone to see you.

17:09.244 --> 17:14.708
I hope you've got a new angle because
it's all pretty much been covered.

17:14.790 --> 17:16.835
Hold on. No one interviews Maggie
in here without a haircut.

17:16.917 --> 17:19.337
Sorry, no.
Just got one.

17:19.420 --> 17:22.673
[Mrs. Pressman]
Excuse me, sir, I have a fact for you.

17:22.714 --> 17:26.510
- This is an actual fact.
- Yes, Mrs. Pressman?

17:26.593 --> 17:29.429
This is actually her fourth wedding,
not her seventh like they said.

17:29.512 --> 17:32.556
[Ike] I know. Tell me something.
Do you think she's...

17:32.640 --> 17:35.642
- gonna make it all the way this time?
- I don't know.

17:35.684 --> 17:38.561
[Gasps]

17:38.645 --> 17:42.440
She swallowed her gum.
She does that.

17:44.024 --> 17:47.360
Mr. Schulian, he runs the newsstand.
He's also our local bookie.

17:47.402 --> 17:49.362
He's given eight-to-one odds
that she won't.

17:49.446 --> 17:51.697
Okay.

17:51.739 --> 17:54.617
Instead of a haircut,
how 'bout a wash?

17:54.700 --> 17:56.785
Get all that city grit
out of your hair.

17:56.868 --> 17:58.787
You'll answer my questions?

17:58.870 --> 18:00.788
Mm-hmm.

18:00.872 --> 18:04.333
Fine! You wash, I'll ask.

18:04.416 --> 18:07.044
So, what do you want to know?

18:07.127 --> 18:09.045
When is the big day?

18:09.129 --> 18:13.132
- A week from Sunday.
- Let's put this here like this...

18:13.215 --> 18:16.218
because this aroma therapy
can get a little strong.

18:16.301 --> 18:18.553
The lavender,
we don't want to put you to sleep.

18:18.595 --> 18:20.096
[Ike] You nervous?

18:20.180 --> 18:22.807
I've never been more certain
of anything in my life.

18:22.890 --> 18:26.602
Except I've been having
all kinds of weird dreams.

18:26.685 --> 18:29.437
Mm-hmm. Would you like
to tell me about 'em?

18:29.521 --> 18:31.439
Yeah, sure.

18:31.522 --> 18:35.151
- [Maggie] And another one.
- Pete, I'll be right with ya.

18:35.234 --> 18:38.362
[Maggie] I go inside the church
and everyone I know is there.

18:38.445 --> 18:42.907
The creepiest part is
I look down at my dress, and it's red!

18:42.990 --> 18:46.160
I don't know what that means.
Red is not my color.

18:48.120 --> 18:50.080
What do you think?

18:50.121 --> 18:52.624
- I think you'd look good in red.
- No, no.

18:54.417 --> 18:58.045
She means about your hair.

18:59.838 --> 19:01.840
[Peggy Chuckles]

19:06.218 --> 19:09.221
My jacket, please.

19:09.304 --> 19:11.890
Thank you.

19:11.931 --> 19:17.311
Excuse me, sir. Do you know where I can
get some shampoo? Strong shampoo?

19:17.394 --> 19:21.147
Doc's pharmacy. Third and Elm.
Tell 'em Pete sent ya.

19:21.231 --> 19:23.191
You want my hat?

19:23.274 --> 19:27.111
No, no, I'm fine.
You might need it.

19:34.784 --> 19:39.163
Mr. Graham, if you're looking
for Elm Street, it's that way.

19:39.246 --> 19:41.414
Thank you.

19:41.498 --> 19:44.459
If you came down here in the pursuit of
happiness, you might as well go back...

19:44.500 --> 19:46.586
because you can't make me feel bad.

19:46.627 --> 19:50.839
I'm not trying to make you feel bad.
I'm here for vindication.

19:50.922 --> 19:54.008
In my heart,
I feel I'm right about you.

19:54.092 --> 19:55.676
Mmm.

19:55.760 --> 19:57.803
You got me fired, lady.

19:57.887 --> 20:02.641
You destroyed my reputation,
and you screwed up my hair.

20:02.682 --> 20:05.643
You chew up men,
spit 'em out and love it.

20:05.727 --> 20:08.896
You're gonna do the same thing
to this poor schmuck number four...

20:08.979 --> 20:11.440
that you did
to the previous three.

20:11.481 --> 20:13.441
You're gonna run again.

20:13.483 --> 20:15.735
And I'm not leaving until you do.

20:17.153 --> 20:21.532
I'd love to stay and chat,
but I still have my job.

20:28.371 --> 20:30.914
Hey, kid, kid, kid,
wait a minute.

20:30.998 --> 20:32.958
- Give you ten bucks for the hat.
- Sure!

20:32.999 --> 20:35.627
That's right.

20:39.505 --> 20:41.507
Sheesh.

20:49.013 --> 20:51.015
[Bob Chuckles]

20:51.056 --> 20:54.226
I'm telling you,
that is a photo opportunity.

20:54.309 --> 20:57.937
When I only see one dog,
I know I've had too much to drink.

20:59.647 --> 21:01.774
Hey, you'll never guess...

21:01.857 --> 21:06.236
who came crawling into town
with his tail between his legs.

21:06.319 --> 21:08.237
[Walter]
Who?

21:08.321 --> 21:10.406
Hello, Maggie.

21:10.489 --> 21:14.034
[Ike] I just came over
to apologize to your family.

21:14.117 --> 21:16.369
When I'm wrong, I'm wrong.

21:16.453 --> 21:19.205
I pushed a story.
I made a mistake.

21:19.288 --> 21:24.543
In other words, he's only human.
And he brought us a bottle of wine.

21:24.626 --> 21:28.421
-Made me put my hat back on.
-Yeah. It scared the hell outta Skipper.

21:28.504 --> 21:30.172
[Barks]

21:30.256 --> 21:32.466
You've gotta be kidding me.

21:32.549 --> 21:34.885
No, no. You should've seen Skipper.
He was like-- [Barks]

21:36.595 --> 21:39.180
[Howls]

21:41.140 --> 21:43.308
It wasn't that... funny.

21:43.392 --> 21:46.228
Actually, it's been quite amusing.

21:46.269 --> 21:50.106
Walter, here, has been sharing his
father of the bride wedding memories.

21:50.189 --> 21:52.775
You know what?

21:52.858 --> 21:56.778
I think I'll take this to the kitchen.
[Mouthing Words]

21:56.862 --> 22:00.698
I'll help you bring it in...
to the kitchen.

22:00.740 --> 22:02.992
- Check on the crabs, Bob.
- Okay.

22:03.075 --> 22:05.410
-[Whispers] Is he staying for dinner?
-I don't know.

22:05.452 --> 22:09.122
I hope they don't have a fight. You
don't think they'd call it off, do you?

22:09.205 --> 22:13.584
Wedding cake freezes. This we know.
[Chuckles]

22:13.626 --> 22:18.129
- You know, your daughter is such--
- [Gasps] Oh, I'm sorry.

22:18.213 --> 22:20.798
No, no, that's all right,
Grandma. That's fine.

22:20.882 --> 22:22.842
She's such a lovely girl.

22:22.925 --> 22:25.761
Yeah. Well,
like her mother. Look.

22:25.844 --> 22:28.138
May she rest in peace.

22:28.221 --> 22:31.099
We were all so proud of Maggie
when she was in school.

22:31.140 --> 22:34.643
She won that American Legion
scholarship to college.

22:34.727 --> 22:36.478
She studied industrial design.

22:36.562 --> 22:40.315
I can't see her leaving multiple grooms
in the dust like that.

22:40.398 --> 22:43.317
Oh, yes, you can.
She's got it all on tape.

22:44.610 --> 22:48.447
- Tape?
- Yeah, they're all right there.

22:48.488 --> 22:50.782
You got tapes of the wedding?

22:50.824 --> 22:52.909
Lee, at the hotel,
videos weddings.

22:52.992 --> 22:58.205
Course Maggie didn't know she was
gonna be running the 100-yarddash.

22:58.288 --> 23:01.958
- I gotta say, she makes real good time.
- Bingo!

23:02.041 --> 23:04.668
Maggie may not be
Hale's longest running joke,

23:04.752 --> 23:06.670
but she is certainly the fastest.

23:06.754 --> 23:09.506
Ha, ha.

23:12.175 --> 23:15.469
Maggie's mom and I
were only blessed with one child,

23:15.511 --> 23:17.513
not for a lack of trying.

23:17.596 --> 23:19.598
This is good, Dad.
Don't leave anything out.

23:20.682 --> 23:22.684
I consider it a bonus...

23:22.767 --> 23:25.436
[Skipper Barks]

23:25.478 --> 23:29.106
that I'm actually able to plan
and pay for so many weddings.

23:29.189 --> 23:31.524
Not this one.
This one's on me.

23:31.608 --> 23:34.235
Oh! That's fair.

23:34.318 --> 23:38.489
I don't do it on purpose, and
I have no intentions of doing it again.

23:38.572 --> 23:41.408
That's right, Maggie.
Just keep your eye on the ball.

23:43.660 --> 23:45.911
Sports psychology.

23:45.995 --> 23:51.499
Bob is the head of
the P.E. department at the high school.

23:51.583 --> 23:55.253
And he coaches the football team.
And he's climbed Everest.

23:57.338 --> 24:00.090
- Everest? Is it true?
- [Maggie] Twice.

24:00.173 --> 24:01.925
Without oxygen.

24:02.008 --> 24:05.136
- My girl, she likes to brag about me.
- I do.

24:06.262 --> 24:09.306
Maggie's training
for our wedding night.

24:09.389 --> 24:11.975
I'm taking her trekking on Annapurna
for our honeymoon.

24:12.058 --> 24:15.269
- Oh, how romantic!
- We think so.

24:15.353 --> 24:19.773
Nothing like sharing your nuptial bed
with two Sherpas and a yak.

24:19.857 --> 24:22.108
[Laughing]

24:24.569 --> 24:27.571
Hey, Ike, how's it going?

24:27.655 --> 24:31.366
You won't believe what
I'm looking at here. I got a video...

24:31.450 --> 24:33.368
of all three train wrecks.

24:33.451 --> 24:37.747
[Chavez]
Here's my bride, who's my pride.

24:37.830 --> 24:40.290
I'll never hide
when she's by my side.

24:40.374 --> 24:42.876
This is for you, Maggie,
my "Sugar Magnolia."

24:42.959 --> 24:48.381
[Ike] You want the truth?
You want the facts? I got 'em.

24:52.884 --> 24:55.053
I'll send you a copy
of the notes.

24:55.136 --> 24:57.263
Good weekend reading for you.

24:57.346 --> 24:59.223
Love to Ellie. Okay, bye.

25:01.517 --> 25:03.643
[Male Singer]
% Sweet blossom come on %

25:03.768 --> 25:05.019
% Under the willow %

25:05.103 --> 25:07.772
% We can have high times
if you'll abide %

25:07.855 --> 25:10.608
% We can discover
the wonders of nature %

25:10.649 --> 25:15.779
% Rolling in the rushes
down by the riverside %

25:17.321 --> 25:19.740
% She's got everything
delightful %

25:19.824 --> 25:22.701
% She's got everything I need %

25:22.784 --> 25:25.954
% Takes the wheel
when I'm seeing double %

25:26.037 --> 25:28.581
% Pays my ticket when I speed %

25:30.791 --> 25:32.709
[Music Stops]

25:32.793 --> 25:35.795
Okay, preacher man, let's go!

25:35.837 --> 25:39.465
-[Chavez] Maggie, where're you goin'?
-[Maggie] Sam!

25:39.507 --> 25:42.843
-[Maggie]Sam. Get back on the bike.
-Okay. How was the wedding?

25:42.926 --> 25:46.721
Shorter than we planned.
Just go.

25:46.805 --> 25:49.640
[Chavez]
Okay, peace, baby.

25:51.517 --> 25:53.519
[Video Fast-Forwarding]

25:53.602 --> 25:55.604
%[Organ]

26:15.829 --> 26:19.415
[Female Singer]
% ["Ave Maria"]

26:32.384 --> 26:36.221
[Concerned Murmuring]

26:36.304 --> 26:40.016
-[Man] Where is she going?
-[Woman] Look, she's leaving.

26:40.058 --> 26:44.228
- [Woman #2] She forgot her purse.
- No, she didn't forget her purse.

26:44.311 --> 26:46.980
[Walter]
Go after her! Do something!

26:50.400 --> 26:52.693
[Chuckles]
I don't believe this.

27:14.712 --> 27:17.422
[Minister] Dearly beloved,
we're gathered here today--

27:17.506 --> 27:20.050
[Whinnies]

27:20.133 --> 27:24.470
Could we hold the horse, please?
What's wrong with the horse?

27:24.553 --> 27:28.140
The horse seems more jittery
than the bride.

27:55.079 --> 27:56.747
I like the white tuxedo.

27:56.789 --> 27:59.082
Yeah, but he's no good
'cause he's too blond.

27:59.166 --> 28:02.293
All right. Then we just go
with something very traditional.

28:02.377 --> 28:06.422
He's handsome.
Maybe a little too dark for Bob.

28:06.463 --> 28:09.925
Yeah, but he's got
the "Bobster's" eyes.

28:09.966 --> 28:13.428
No, no, no, no. The Bobster's eyes
are closer set. Yeah.

28:13.469 --> 28:15.680
- Hello! Hi.
- Hi.

28:15.763 --> 28:18.891
-Could I have two cups of coffee? And--
-Yes.

28:18.974 --> 28:21.685
[Sniffs]
Mmm. What is that wonderful smell?

28:21.768 --> 28:24.312
Oh, the cinnamon rolls!

28:24.395 --> 28:26.730
- Could I have two of those? Thank you.
- Yeah, sure.

28:26.814 --> 28:30.233
Okay. Uh, Maggie,
I think this makes the best you.

28:30.400 --> 28:31.860
[Whispering] Okay.

28:31.943 --> 28:36.906
Oh, let's see. Look at that.

28:36.989 --> 28:39.032
Excuse me.

28:39.116 --> 28:42.827
Oh, look at that.

28:42.911 --> 28:45.580
Bam, bam, bam, bam, bam!

28:45.663 --> 28:50.292
Ow, ow, ow!
Help me! Help me!

28:50.334 --> 28:53.211
[Sighs]
Yep, that'd be her.

28:54.837 --> 28:57.631
You must be
that Mr. Graham fella.

28:57.673 --> 28:59.800
- Yes, I am! And you are?
- [Laughing]

28:59.842 --> 29:02.719
- I'm Betty Trout.
- Hi, Betty!

29:02.802 --> 29:06.139
Okay, I guess you'll be
the one making the cake.

29:06.180 --> 29:08.015
Yes, I am. Sure.

29:08.099 --> 29:10.934
I'm also told
that you will be throwing--

29:11.018 --> 29:13.645
I'm throwing the luau for Maggie.

29:13.687 --> 29:16.481
Pre-wedding luau!

29:16.564 --> 29:18.691
If you're still in town,
you should stop by.

29:18.774 --> 29:20.734
No, no, he doesn't want to come.

29:20.818 --> 29:22.861
I'd love to come.
[Bell Rings]

29:22.944 --> 29:25.572
I will be there. Thank you.

29:25.655 --> 29:29.658
Is that what you're going to do now?
Follow me around everywhere I go?

29:29.742 --> 29:30.909
No.

29:30.993 --> 29:34.079
I'll be back, Betty.

29:34.162 --> 29:37.040
Bye, Mr. Graham.

29:37.081 --> 29:39.417
- He's not a nice person.
- Well, I know.

29:39.500 --> 29:43.128
That's my pick.
The eyes are perfect.

29:43.211 --> 29:47.465
[Cheerleaders]
We always win. We never fail.

29:47.548 --> 29:51.969
We're the Comets, so go to Hale!
% Let's go, Comets %

29:52.052 --> 29:55.722
% Let's go
Let's go, Comets, let's go %

29:55.805 --> 29:58.766
- Hi, Miss Carpenter.
- Hey, Kendall.

30:00.184 --> 30:04.980
Maggie, don't marry Coach.
Marry me. I love you.

30:05.063 --> 30:09.859
You're jail bait, Dennis. Go away.
Go away. Run your laps. Go, go!

30:09.900 --> 30:14.112
[Bob]
Drive, drive, drive! From the hips!

30:14.196 --> 30:16.364
Keep it low now, keep it low!

30:16.448 --> 30:20.076
[Whistle Blows] Good job, gentlemen.
All right, special teams.

30:20.159 --> 30:22.745
Special teams.

30:22.828 --> 30:25.705
- Hey, honey, how are you?
- Good.

30:25.747 --> 30:28.583
What is he up to now?

30:28.666 --> 30:30.918
Ike just dropped by
to check out the team.

30:31.001 --> 30:32.670
And to talk about you!

30:32.753 --> 30:34.546
- Ahh!
- Yes!

30:34.630 --> 30:37.090
You aren't making friends
with this man, are you?

30:37.132 --> 30:40.509
I'm just bragging
about how good you are.

30:40.593 --> 30:44.012
- And how I'm the luckiest man alive.
- Mm-hmm!

30:45.180 --> 30:46.890
Sweetie.

30:46.932 --> 30:50.434
Well, I better be moving.

30:50.518 --> 30:52.937
Got a lot of work to do today.

30:52.978 --> 30:55.397
- See you two lovebirds later.
- See you at the weddin'.

30:55.439 --> 30:59.359
- Yeah. Thanks for the jacket.
- You invited him to the wedding?

30:59.442 --> 31:03.445
% Go, go, Comets
Let's go %

31:03.529 --> 31:05.739
Don't you realize he's writing
another article about me?

31:05.781 --> 31:06.615
Sure.

31:06.698 --> 31:12.370
But you're not runnin'. Come on. Give
me some of that homemade sunshine.

31:12.453 --> 31:17.165
Boys, take my princess
for a ride on her chariot.

31:17.249 --> 31:19.084
Oh, my--
[Laughing]

31:25.464 --> 31:27.716
Bless me, Father,
for I have sinned.

31:27.799 --> 31:32.261
My last confession was--
Well, anyway.

31:32.345 --> 31:35.097
I have sort of
a technical question.

31:35.180 --> 31:38.225
I've been having bad thoughts.

31:38.308 --> 31:41.144
Reallybadthoughts.

31:41.227 --> 31:44.105
- Of an impure nature?
- No, no.

31:44.146 --> 31:50.068
I want to destroy this man's life,
career, everything. I want revenge!

31:50.151 --> 31:53.487
Now, on the sin scale,
howbadis that?

31:53.571 --> 31:56.865
Can I... "Hail Mary"
my way out of that?

31:56.949 --> 32:00.493
-My child, any sin in one's heart is a--
-The name is Maggie.

32:00.577 --> 32:03.120
It was this side of ten years ago
you had your tongue down my throat.

32:03.204 --> 32:06.248
So don't "my child" me, Brian, okay?
It annoys me.

32:06.332 --> 32:08.709
Maggie, don't get so upset.

32:08.792 --> 32:11.961
Hey, hey! Don't-- Brian, talk to me.
I need to talk to you.

32:12.045 --> 32:13.546
Maggie, Maggie, Maggie.

32:13.629 --> 32:16.298
You're not even Catholic
so you really shouldn't be here.

32:16.382 --> 32:20.343
I'm sorry. I'm just so stressed out
about this slimeball reporter.

32:20.385 --> 32:23.346
And I wanted to come and tell you
that he might stop by here...

32:23.387 --> 32:25.723
and ask you all kinds
of ridiculous questions.

32:25.806 --> 32:28.767
Well, he only actually asked me
one ridiculous question.

32:28.850 --> 32:30.810
The rest weren't so bad.

32:30.852 --> 32:34.522
What? Oh, you talked to him?

32:34.605 --> 32:37.941
Did you tell him
we dated before you were a priest?

32:38.025 --> 32:41.528
Of course.
I think I only did you good.

32:41.611 --> 32:43.863
W-What exactly did he ask?

32:43.946 --> 32:47.491
- Am I too late, Father?
- No, no.

32:47.533 --> 32:51.036
- It won't take long. Just two venials.
- Okay.

32:51.119 --> 32:53.580
Um, just respectful things.

32:53.663 --> 32:56.999
What kind of music did you like?
What did we have in common?

32:57.082 --> 33:01.169
Did you ruin my life
when you left me at the altar?

33:01.253 --> 33:03.713
Uh, what did you say?

33:03.796 --> 33:06.257
I said, you know,
how could I be angry...

33:06.340 --> 33:11.344
when this is clearly as God
intended for it to be for me?

33:11.470 --> 33:13.805
Good one! Thanks.

33:13.888 --> 33:18.767
But, actually,
it's, it's really, really how I feel.

33:21.436 --> 33:22.854
Of course. God, yes.

33:22.937 --> 33:24.939
Not... [Whispers] God.

33:25.023 --> 33:26.482
[Whispers]
Sorry.

33:26.566 --> 33:28.776
I better go.
The man is a lunatic.

33:28.859 --> 33:31.695
But I think I know exactly
where he's going next.

33:31.778 --> 33:33.697
[Whispering]
God bless.

33:35.114 --> 33:37.366
Oh! Purse.

33:37.450 --> 33:40.494
Forgot my purse.

33:40.577 --> 33:42.913
Hi, sorry. Purse.

33:42.996 --> 33:45.206
Good luck.

33:45.290 --> 33:48.000
What was the one ridiculous question
that he asked?

33:48.084 --> 33:51.170
He wanted to know
how you liked your eggs.

33:51.253 --> 33:53.046
Oh, weird.

33:53.129 --> 33:55.256
Like a person's gonna
remember after all this time.

33:55.340 --> 33:59.301
Scrambled with salt, pepper and dill.
Same as me.

34:03.430 --> 34:05.765
I'm sorry I hurt you, Brian.

34:07.391 --> 34:11.562
Maggie, I'm happy now... here.
It's where I'm supposed to be.

34:11.645 --> 34:16.024
But... if you ever do decide to become
a Catholic, will you do me this favor?

34:16.107 --> 34:18.025
Confess to Father Patrick.

34:18.109 --> 34:20.694
Of course.

34:35.498 --> 34:38.042
- Gill? Lydia?
- Mags!

34:38.126 --> 34:40.878
Hey, look, the tape. Remember?

34:40.960 --> 34:42.920
Radio City Music Hall concert...

34:43.005 --> 34:45.966
when Jerry was on "Ripple,"
and I'm going like, "Dude, let me jam."

34:46.049 --> 34:48.092
- Gill, listen--
- I'll play it for you.

34:48.176 --> 34:51.094
- You remember, Maggie. You were there.
- Can you focus on me?

34:51.178 --> 34:53.931
There's this reporter
who's making my life a living hell.

34:54.014 --> 34:55.348
Okay.

34:55.431 --> 34:58.059
And whatever you do,

34:58.142 --> 35:02.062
do not show him that picture of me
from the concert in San Francisco.

35:02.146 --> 35:04.189
- Okay? Can you--
- [Ike Laughing]

35:04.273 --> 35:08.651
- What is that?
- Uh-- Wait. San Francisco?

35:08.735 --> 35:11.278
But we went there a few times.
There's a lot of pictures.

35:11.362 --> 35:14.364
Which picture? Because one time
we had a flat tire. Remember?

35:14.448 --> 35:16.116
Imagine!

35:16.199 --> 35:21.620
Maggie Carpenter
topless in a public arena.

35:21.662 --> 35:24.331
Mmm. Oh, yeah.

35:24.414 --> 35:27.625
I see it was
a very chilly evening.

35:27.709 --> 35:29.961
Mm-hmm.

35:32.963 --> 35:35.882
What's really interesting
about this, though,

35:35.966 --> 35:39.886
is that you can't see
that rose tattoo...

35:39.969 --> 35:43.722
- on your back.
- [Chuckles]

35:43.806 --> 35:47.475
Oh, yeah. Ike bet me 50 bucks
that you don't still have it.

35:47.559 --> 35:50.895
I said, "You're on, man.
Maggie loved that thing."

35:50.978 --> 35:53.981
And, seriously, I mean,
I could use 50 bucks.

35:54.064 --> 35:57.150
- Mm-hmm.
- Maggie?

35:57.234 --> 35:59.152
Just--

36:02.947 --> 36:05.157
Look, I'm not gonna show
you guys anything.

36:05.199 --> 36:08.994
I am a soon-to-be-married woman.
So just give me the photograph!

36:09.035 --> 36:11.079
I would love to give you this.
Believe me, I would.

36:11.162 --> 36:15.040
Just give us a quick gander
at that rose,

36:15.124 --> 36:17.042
and I'll gladly
turn it over to you.

36:17.125 --> 36:19.919
Fine. Fine. Okay, fine.

36:21.671 --> 36:24.006
Okay? All right?

36:24.048 --> 36:26.800
- [Clears Throat] Satisfied?
- Completely.

36:26.884 --> 36:31.471
- Maggie, you got it removed?
- Gill--

36:31.554 --> 36:34.974
Gill, I'll go you double or nothing
it was a stick on.

36:37.017 --> 36:38.935
Maggie?

36:42.689 --> 36:45.316
Gill, I am...

36:45.399 --> 36:48.193
really, really...

36:48.277 --> 36:50.987
afraid of needles.

36:51.071 --> 36:53.156
- But that doesn't make me a bad person.
- Look.

36:53.239 --> 36:56.200
Look! Look!

36:56.242 --> 36:58.577
I think this man is heartbroken.

36:58.660 --> 37:00.829
- No, he's not.
- I think I am.

37:02.163 --> 37:04.498
No, you're, you're not!

37:04.582 --> 37:08.210
You have your guitar,
and you have Lydia. You're not--

37:08.293 --> 37:11.129
% [Guitar]

37:11.212 --> 37:14.549
We'll talk about this later. Okay?

37:19.928 --> 37:22.222
Hey, Ike?

37:22.305 --> 37:25.516
- What would Jerry do?
- He'd play.

37:25.600 --> 37:28.352
-Jerry would play!
- He would play!

37:40.862 --> 37:42.781
Well, there's Ike...

37:42.864 --> 37:45.241
with the mayor
and the police chief.

37:45.283 --> 37:47.284
Boy, he sure makes friends easy.

37:47.326 --> 37:50.287
That's pretty cool.

37:57.918 --> 37:59.711
- Oh, yeah!
- That's right!

38:04.799 --> 38:07.260
- Hey, you're that reporter, right?
- Yeah.

38:07.343 --> 38:09.762
There he is again!

38:09.845 --> 38:12.013
Snoop Doggy Dogg!

38:12.097 --> 38:15.308
- I'm going to marry Maggie someday.
- Oh, really?

38:15.391 --> 38:18.769
He's an attractive man.

38:18.811 --> 38:22.522
The vicious reporter is attractive?
You're saying viciousness is attractive?

38:22.606 --> 38:24.774
No, I'm not saying
viciousness is attractive.

38:28.611 --> 38:30.321
He's coming.

38:30.404 --> 38:31.738
I better go--

38:31.822 --> 38:34.324
No, no, no.
Don't leave. Uh, act natural.

38:34.407 --> 38:37.577
- Okay.
- He can probably read lips.

38:37.660 --> 38:41.663
The famous Swenson triplets.
Gimme 15. Yeah, yeah, yeah. Well done.

38:41.747 --> 38:45.125
- I will handle this.
- Don't move your lips! Okay? Go on.

38:45.166 --> 38:48.794
I will handle this!
I won't say anything.

38:48.836 --> 38:51.046
- Okay.
- I'll handle it.

38:52.881 --> 38:56.676
Yeah, Cory!

38:56.759 --> 38:58.719
- Hey, Peggy Flemming!
- Hey.

38:58.803 --> 39:01.472
- Not the ice skater.
- That's Maggie's seat.

39:01.513 --> 39:04.141
Yes, and this must be her beer too.

39:04.224 --> 39:06.309
- [Cory]Hey!
- Hey, sweetie!

39:06.392 --> 39:09.312
[Ike]
That your husband out here?

39:09.395 --> 39:12.314
- Yeah.
- This is Cory? Cory Flemming?

39:12.356 --> 39:14.649
He's a radio announcer here,
isn't he?

39:14.691 --> 39:18.069
Yeah, that's right. Have you heard his
morning show, "Wake up with Flemm"?

39:19.654 --> 39:21.572
Not yet.

39:21.655 --> 39:26.076
[Grandma Over P.A.]Now up,
Atlantic Hotel's Lee Mistlehorne.

39:26.159 --> 39:28.202
He actually made
the all-stars in high school.

39:28.286 --> 39:30.538
Really?
You must be proud of him.

39:30.621 --> 39:32.539
I didn't really
know him back then.

39:32.623 --> 39:37.460
He was actually dating Maggie...
at the time.

39:37.544 --> 39:42.006
I mean, he never really--
They were never gonna...

39:42.089 --> 39:44.925
get engaged or anything,
it was just like, you know.

39:45.008 --> 39:47.927
Sometimes he'd call her Magpie,
and it was really irritating.

39:48.011 --> 39:50.972
But-- I don't know why
I'm telling you this.

39:51.055 --> 39:52.515
No, this is good.

39:55.017 --> 39:57.310
- He's stealing third!
- Yes!

39:57.394 --> 39:59.103
[Bob]
Safe.

39:59.187 --> 40:01.856
Excellent.

40:05.359 --> 40:07.736
Yes! Yes! Whoo!

40:09.237 --> 40:11.530
Safe!

40:11.614 --> 40:15.117
- I love it!
- Uh-huh!

40:15.200 --> 40:17.827
- Good one!
- Magpie!

40:19.787 --> 40:21.706
Just--

40:21.789 --> 40:23.707
Excellent!

40:25.334 --> 40:29.504
It's nice that
they're... still friends.

40:31.631 --> 40:36.385
Yeah, I mean, that was just a long time
ago. And, you know, it's just--

40:38.762 --> 40:41.681
So-- Excuse me.

40:41.764 --> 40:44.475
- You all right?
- Yeah!

40:44.558 --> 40:47.144
[Grandma Over P.A.] That makes it
Alumni, nine, Hale students, eight.

40:47.227 --> 40:50.813
- Hey, Peggy?
- Hey!

40:50.897 --> 40:55.901
[Grandma] Cookies for today's game
were donated by Betty Trout.

40:57.110 --> 41:01.030
Now up for the Comets,
Jordan Hill.

41:01.114 --> 41:03.074
You have been here,
what, like three minutes?

41:03.157 --> 41:04.617
What did you do to her?

41:04.700 --> 41:09.121
-You could just turn that finger around.
-Excuse me?

41:09.204 --> 41:12.957
Oh, Cory, Cory, Cory!
Pow, pow, pow, pow. What is this about?

41:13.040 --> 41:15.960
You know what? We have all
been friends our entire lives.

41:16.043 --> 41:18.920
A type of relationship
that you obviously don't understand.

41:19.004 --> 41:22.298
I'm not the only one
who does not understand.

41:22.382 --> 41:25.968
The U.S.S. Maggie
leaves quite a wake.

41:26.051 --> 41:28.011
Excuse me.

41:33.182 --> 41:37.061
Pot-stirrer man.

41:43.858 --> 41:46.318
[Grandma] Cory Flemming
to Lee Mistlehorne to Dr. Ettinger.

41:46.402 --> 41:49.154
Hey. All right.

41:50.322 --> 41:53.074
That's cheering.
I'm cheering normal.

41:53.157 --> 41:56.202
Cheer. Normal.

41:58.370 --> 42:02.332
- [Woman] Good morning, Peggy.
- Good morning.

42:12.299 --> 42:15.009
Do you think I flirt with Cory?

42:16.677 --> 42:20.639
Good morning to you too.
You look good.

42:20.681 --> 42:23.433
Thank you.

42:23.516 --> 42:25.893
Do you think I flirt with Cory?

42:25.977 --> 42:29.813
- Yes.
- I don't mean to.

42:29.897 --> 42:33.066
I know. I think sometimes
you just sort of...

42:33.149 --> 42:36.527
spaz out with excess
flirtatious energy,

42:36.569 --> 42:40.405
and it just lands
on anything male that moves.

42:40.489 --> 42:43.241
Anything male that moves?

42:43.325 --> 42:46.744
As opposed to anything male
that doesn't?

42:48.245 --> 42:51.748
Well, like certain kinds of coral.

42:52.749 --> 42:55.543
I'm definitely going to have
to kill myself today.

42:55.585 --> 42:56.586
Why?

42:56.669 --> 43:00.714
Because you think I'm all like,
"Hey, man, check me out."

43:00.798 --> 43:05.343
No, I don't.
I think you're like...

43:05.426 --> 43:09.388
"I'm charming and mysterious
in a way that even I don't understand,

43:09.430 --> 43:15.143
and something about me is crying out
for protection from a big man like you."

43:15.226 --> 43:17.270
It's very hard to compete with.

43:17.353 --> 43:21.023
Especially as... married women
who've lost our mystery.

43:21.106 --> 43:25.276
Lost-- You have--
You are totally mysterious.

43:25.360 --> 43:27.403
No. I'm weird.

43:27.487 --> 43:31.240
Weird and mysterious
are two very different things.

43:31.323 --> 43:34.743
- I'm weird.
- No, you're quirky.

43:34.784 --> 43:39.580
Quirky and weird
are two very different things.

43:41.582 --> 43:45.877
Peggy, I think there
is a distinct possibility...

43:45.961 --> 43:50.381
that I am profoundly
and irreversibly screwed up.

43:52.132 --> 43:54.051
Despite that,

43:54.134 --> 43:57.512
I love you and I promise...

43:57.595 --> 43:59.931
to no longer flirt with Cory.

44:01.390 --> 44:04.768
Maggie, I'm not worried
about you and Cory,

44:04.810 --> 44:07.312
or me and Cory,

44:07.395 --> 44:11.190
or you being
irreversibly screwed up.

44:11.273 --> 44:14.568
Maggie, you've been like this
since we were kids.

44:14.651 --> 44:19.072
And all I'm thinking is,
now that you're aware of it,

44:19.155 --> 44:21.449
and that it hurts
people's feelings sometimes,

44:21.490 --> 44:26.411
maybe it's time to get on with life,
and commit to someone of your own,

44:26.495 --> 44:29.247
like Bob, if he's the one.

44:30.373 --> 44:32.291
I know.

44:35.836 --> 44:39.589
Is there anything I can do to...
make it up to you?

44:39.672 --> 44:43.425
Well, there's always...

44:43.509 --> 44:47.304
the thing that brings
warmth to my heart,

44:47.387 --> 44:49.347
and that is duckbill platypus.

44:49.430 --> 44:53.642
Duckbill-- That is only funny
in like Camp Birchwood on...

44:53.726 --> 44:55.477
Just do it.

44:55.519 --> 44:57.812
a trip with the tent and my leg
as the pole and it's raining.

44:57.854 --> 44:59.814
And you know.
That's the only time that's funny.

44:59.856 --> 45:02.983
Let's just see.

45:04.693 --> 45:06.320
Oh.

45:12.700 --> 45:15.828
[Chuckling]

45:17.204 --> 45:20.039
It's so humiliating.

45:20.123 --> 45:21.874
Thank you.

45:23.668 --> 45:25.794
Thank you.

45:26.003 --> 45:28.255
[Barbershop Quartet]
% Farewell, ladies %

45:28.338 --> 45:32.508
% Farewell, ladies
We're going to leave you now %

45:32.550 --> 45:36.845
% Merrily we roll along
roll along, roll along %

45:38.555 --> 45:41.474
Lee. Hey, wake up. Hey!

45:41.558 --> 45:43.351
- Hello?
- Hi.

45:43.434 --> 45:46.186
Gimme the key to the reporter's
room. I wanna snoop around.

45:46.270 --> 45:48.355
- Come on, quick. Wake up.
- Second floor.

45:48.438 --> 45:51.357
- Thank you.
- Don't take anything big.

45:51.399 --> 45:53.818
Okay.

46:10.165 --> 46:12.083
Shh.

46:18.255 --> 46:20.173
Hmm.

46:21.424 --> 46:23.384
Hopefully his favorite.

46:23.426 --> 46:26.095
[Fisher Over Cell Phone]
My theory is she's running...

46:26.178 --> 46:28.180
because she gets negative attention.

46:28.263 --> 46:30.223
Negative attention is attention.

46:30.265 --> 46:33.560
You know, like when women whack you
on the street because of your column.

46:33.643 --> 46:35.144
That's negative attention.

46:35.228 --> 46:38.188
We're talking about
her negative attention, not mine.

46:46.946 --> 46:49.573
"How does she get all
those guys to propose?

46:49.656 --> 46:52.575
She's not that beautiful.''

46:52.659 --> 46:55.119
Bite me, paperboy.

46:58.497 --> 47:01.291
Ah, hey! Hey!

47:01.375 --> 47:02.667
Hi, Ike.

47:02.751 --> 47:06.712
You put your shoes out at night,
they're real shiny in the mornin'.

47:06.796 --> 47:10.549
- Sometimes they don't bring 'em back.
- Mmm, why take a chance?

47:10.632 --> 47:12.551
Good night.

47:26.354 --> 47:29.607
All right.
I know you're in there. I saw you.

47:31.567 --> 47:34.277
You realize you're messing
with the First Amendment now.

47:34.361 --> 47:37.613
[Knocking On Door]
Come on, open up.

47:37.697 --> 47:39.990
Come on!

47:40.074 --> 47:42.075
We should have
a very serious discussion...

47:42.117 --> 47:44.911
about why you are
such a pain in the ass!

47:44.953 --> 47:46.454
Open the door!

47:46.496 --> 47:49.123
I'm coming in.
I'm coming through.

47:49.206 --> 47:51.333
It's your last chance.
Here I come!

47:51.417 --> 47:53.251
Here I come!

47:55.003 --> 47:56.963
All right.

47:57.005 --> 48:01.759
Breaking and entering. That's a felony.
I'm calling the sheriff.

48:01.842 --> 48:03.635
You know what?
You do that.

48:03.719 --> 48:07.180
Can you remind him that's he's
bringing the wine to the luau?

48:07.263 --> 48:11.100
[Whispering]
It'll save me a call. Thanks so much.

48:11.141 --> 48:13.268
Hey, Ike, does your friend
have a sister?

48:13.352 --> 48:16.938
Wait for the original.
She'll be available in a week.

48:20.524 --> 48:23.318
%[Jazz]

48:47.213 --> 48:49.298
[Maggie Crowing]

48:49.340 --> 48:52.468
[Crowing Continues]

48:52.551 --> 48:55.846
[Crowing]

48:58.556 --> 49:02.476
Freeze. Oh, hold on to those covers.
I didn't come to see Ike Junior.

49:02.560 --> 49:07.355
[Sighs] I take it the desk clerk
is one of your many admirers.

49:09.023 --> 49:13.027
So, your notes made for...
interesting reading.

49:13.110 --> 49:14.611
What's your point?

49:14.695 --> 49:16.905
My point is, once again,
you're getting it all wrong.

49:16.988 --> 49:19.365
And that's not gonna improve
your reputation,

49:19.449 --> 49:21.993
and it's not very flattering
to me either.

49:22.034 --> 49:26.038
So, I decided that I would
help you write the truth.

49:26.121 --> 49:27.956
- [Chuckles] Really?
- Mm-hmm.

49:28.039 --> 49:30.958
Oh.

49:31.042 --> 49:35.212
I've decided to cooperate
and let you interview me...

49:35.254 --> 49:38.381
- for $1,000.
- [Groans]

49:38.465 --> 49:40.550
I want a big wedding
and a killer dress.

49:40.633 --> 49:45.888
And for a grand, I will answer all your
questions and let you follow me around.

49:45.929 --> 49:50.225
The magazine does not
spend money for stories.

49:50.266 --> 49:52.393
- It's not what you would call ethical.
- Oh.

49:52.477 --> 49:54.603
I meant you.

49:54.687 --> 49:58.899
I figured you probably
got severance or expenses or both.

49:58.940 --> 50:02.235
I'm guessing
that you're writing on spec.

50:02.276 --> 50:06.238
And with a first-person interview,
you might actually sell that thing.

50:06.280 --> 50:09.783
- Too much.
- Seven-fifty.

50:09.950 --> 50:11.909
- Five hundred.
- Six-fifty.

50:11.951 --> 50:15.037
Done.

50:15.121 --> 50:18.999
% [Ike Whistling Tune To
"The Andy Griffith Show"]

50:19.082 --> 50:23.169
Is that supposed to be a joke?
I know what you're whistling.

50:23.252 --> 50:25.171
- Hello.
- Hi.

50:27.464 --> 50:30.467
This is a birthday present
for my cousin.

50:30.508 --> 50:32.010
[Motor Whirring]

50:32.093 --> 50:35.262
[Chuckles]
That's great.

50:35.346 --> 50:39.933
Wonderful stuff. All these found
industrial parts and things.

50:40.016 --> 50:41.976
A lamp tree.

50:42.018 --> 50:43.978
That's great.

50:44.020 --> 50:47.940
- Is this-- That's your preferred logo?
- I think so.

50:47.981 --> 50:49.983
It's nice. The whole thing is great.

50:50.067 --> 50:52.110
I think you could sell
these lamps in New York.

50:52.193 --> 50:54.612
Maybe someday.

50:54.654 --> 50:58.282
- You afraid to try?
- No, no. I'm not afraid.

50:58.323 --> 51:01.660
Just... someday.

51:03.328 --> 51:05.871
This is Brian.

51:05.955 --> 51:08.207
Oh, Father Brian.

51:08.290 --> 51:12.252
- And Gill's, of course.
- Gill, yeah.

51:12.335 --> 51:15.546
And... George.

51:15.630 --> 51:19.299
He proposed at a butterfly farm
in Saint Thomas.

51:19.341 --> 51:21.426
The ring was inside a cocoon.

51:21.510 --> 51:25.930
Ahh. A little too
Silence of the Lambs for my taste, but--

51:26.013 --> 51:29.058
Well, he's an entomologist.
I thought it was very unique.

51:29.141 --> 51:31.893
- And finally, Bob.
- Mmm.

51:31.977 --> 51:34.229
He proposed during
the seventh inning stretch...

51:36.022 --> 51:39.316
at an Oriole game.

51:39.358 --> 51:42.527
Wait, wait.
Wait, don't tell me.

51:42.611 --> 51:45.905
The scoreboard lit up
with "Marry me, Maggie."

51:45.988 --> 51:48.657
It was one of the most
wonderful moments of my life.

51:48.741 --> 51:51.159
Highly suspect.

51:51.201 --> 51:54.496
What do you mean?
It was incredibly romantic.

51:54.537 --> 51:57.873
Look, maybe it's just me, but...

51:57.957 --> 52:01.793
if you gotta dress it up like that,
it just doesn't ring true.

52:01.877 --> 52:06.297
You know,
l, I think the most...

52:06.381 --> 52:08.758
that anybody
can honestly say is:

52:08.841 --> 52:14.012
"Look, I guarantee there'll be
tough times. I guarantee...

52:14.054 --> 52:18.849
"at some point one or both of us
is gonna want to get out of this thing.

52:18.933 --> 52:23.228
"But I also guarantee that
if I don't ask you to be mine,

52:23.311 --> 52:25.939
"I'll regret it
the rest of my life.

52:26.022 --> 52:30.526
"Because I know in my heart...

52:31.985 --> 52:34.529
you're the only one for me."

52:37.782 --> 52:39.742
I like it.

52:40.868 --> 52:43.161
I'd like it better
on a scoreboard.

52:46.289 --> 52:50.543
So, is that what you said when
you asked your wife to marry you?

52:50.626 --> 52:53.670
Don't look so surprised. You've got
"divorce" written all over you.

52:55.130 --> 52:57.882
I'm a work-in-progress.

52:57.924 --> 53:01.218
So, is that what
you said to her?

53:01.260 --> 53:04.263
No. I think I said
something very eloquent like,

53:04.346 --> 53:06.806
"So, um,

53:06.890 --> 53:09.851
"maybe you and I should,
you know--

53:09.934 --> 53:12.645
What do you think? Huh?''

53:13.937 --> 53:16.231
Now, that's romantic.

53:16.314 --> 53:19.484
And with a proposal like that,
you didn't find eternal bliss?

53:19.567 --> 53:22.403
- [Sighs]
- What went wrong?

53:22.486 --> 53:24.446
I don't know.

53:24.488 --> 53:28.408
- You don't know?
- No.

53:28.449 --> 53:32.536
Maybe you should ask her sometime.
Ever thought of that?

53:32.620 --> 53:35.330
[Chuckles]

53:41.961 --> 53:44.088
[Maggie] Even with
everything that's happened,

53:44.171 --> 53:46.006
I have still never been married.

53:46.089 --> 53:49.676
And I still deserve
a beautiful dress.

53:51.594 --> 53:53.929
- [Doorbells Tinkle]
- Mrs. Whittenmeyer?

53:54.013 --> 53:55.973
Where are you going?

53:56.014 --> 53:58.183
- Hi, Polly.
- Hi, Maggie.

53:58.266 --> 54:01.185
You'll have to excuse her. Some of
the children are afraid of you...

54:01.269 --> 54:03.729
since you dragged
that little boy up the aisle.

54:03.813 --> 54:05.731
Drag-- No.
I didn't, I didn't--

54:05.814 --> 54:08.108
He tripped
on his own shoelaces.

54:08.191 --> 54:11.361
You've come for your dress. Good.
It's in the back. I'll get it.

54:11.444 --> 54:16.156
Actually, Mrs. Whittenmeyer,
I decided...

54:16.240 --> 54:19.117
- that I want to get this dress.
- Oh.

54:19.159 --> 54:22.078
The one you have on hold
is lovely, dear.

54:22.161 --> 54:25.914
I know, but I've just--
I've changed my mind.

54:25.998 --> 54:28.208
This is $ 1 ,000.

54:28.291 --> 54:31.085
And I have $ 1 ,000.

54:31.169 --> 54:34.213
[Mrs. Whittenmeyer]
The other one is only $300, dear.

54:34.296 --> 54:38.633
Um-- Is that dress for sale?

54:38.717 --> 54:43.137
It's just a lot of money to spend
on one of your dresses, Maggie.

54:43.179 --> 54:47.057
After all, you only wear them
for about ten minutes or so.

54:52.395 --> 54:54.355
Um, yeah, yeah.

54:54.438 --> 54:57.608
I guess that's true.

54:59.401 --> 55:02.862
Uh, the other dress is, is nice.

55:02.904 --> 55:05.114
- Mrs. Whittenheimer?
- Meyer.

55:05.197 --> 55:07.866
Whittenmeyer. Could I talk
to you just for a second?

55:07.950 --> 55:10.243
Come here. I don't know much
about this kind of thing.

55:10.327 --> 55:14.789
I'm from out of town.
But you're a salesperson, right?

55:14.872 --> 55:18.000
- You're here to sell wedding dresses.
- I've been here 30 years.

55:18.041 --> 55:21.836
Perfect! Because
Miss Carpenter is here to buy one.

55:21.878 --> 55:24.881
Ah. But not just any one.
She wants that one.

55:24.922 --> 55:28.467
- It's $1,000!
- Listen, Aunt Bee.

55:30.510 --> 55:33.972
Verbal communication was never perfect
for me. Let's try visual, all right?

55:36.390 --> 55:38.600
[Ike]
We're buying the dress.

55:38.684 --> 55:41.353
Now, we'll have
this nice beautiful dress.

55:41.394 --> 55:45.022
And anything else she wants,
it's hers. Okay? All right?

55:52.237 --> 55:54.864
[Sighs]
What do you think?

56:02.537 --> 56:04.455
Hmm?

56:07.958 --> 56:11.003
[Sighs]

56:11.086 --> 56:13.880
You look--

56:20.177 --> 56:22.220
[Sniffs]
You look fine.

56:22.304 --> 56:24.889
Fine.

56:26.516 --> 56:28.517
[Clears Throat]

56:28.601 --> 56:31.353
You're reading your newspaper
upside down.

56:31.436 --> 56:33.730
That's gotta
be better than "fine."

56:33.772 --> 56:36.399
Yeah.

56:36.482 --> 56:38.442
Come on, now.
Admire me.

56:38.484 --> 56:40.736
Get the whole picture.
Right?

56:40.778 --> 56:42.779
I'm gonna have my hair up
somehow.

56:42.863 --> 56:44.823
I don't know.
Maybe with a little in the back.

56:44.906 --> 56:47.825
And, my favorite feature...

56:47.909 --> 56:52.788
is that it kind of swishes
like a bell when I move.

56:54.414 --> 56:56.249
[Maggie]
% Ding, ding %

56:56.332 --> 56:59.210
% Ding, ding %

57:00.961 --> 57:02.880
It works.

57:02.963 --> 57:05.715
Bob will be very happy.

57:05.799 --> 57:10.636
Oh, Bob! We gotta go.
We gotta go meet Bob.

57:10.761 --> 57:14.014
Oh, jeez, yeah, I'm goin' to the luau.
I never miss it. The barbershop--

57:14.056 --> 57:17.225
Mrs. Pressman, we're ready
to order here, I think.

57:17.308 --> 57:19.185
I'm all out of the special--

57:19.227 --> 57:22.187
That's all right. I'm gonna have
the garden omelet, egg whites only.

57:22.229 --> 57:25.023
- Okay.
- That sounds good. I'll have the same.

57:25.065 --> 57:26.566
Of course.

57:26.649 --> 57:30.986
What is that? I can't even order eggs
without sarcasm from you?

57:31.070 --> 57:32.571
[Clears Throat]

57:32.654 --> 57:34.865
- You're on the same team now.
- What is that sound?

57:34.906 --> 57:36.783
[Clears Throat]
Have some water.

57:36.866 --> 57:40.203
- Penalty box. Penalty box. Hmm?
- What is it? Fur ball?

57:40.286 --> 57:43.622
Ike, Maggie is the sweetest person
you're ever gonna meet.

57:43.705 --> 57:45.791
But she focuses too much out there.

57:45.874 --> 57:48.334
She needs to start
focusing more in here.

57:48.418 --> 57:50.920
That's why I think
she's had, uh,

57:51.003 --> 57:56.091
whatever you wanna call 'em--
problems in the past.

57:56.174 --> 57:58.885
And that's what
we're working on. Focus.

57:58.927 --> 58:02.388
-Focus. Focus on Maggie. Focus.
- Mm-hmm.

58:02.471 --> 58:05.390
Focus on Bob. Focus on Bob.

58:05.474 --> 58:08.351
I've been runnin' Maggie
through these visualization exercises.

58:08.435 --> 58:11.103
All the sports shrinks
use this head stuff.

58:11.187 --> 58:13.689
Visualize the end zone.

58:13.772 --> 58:18.234
Visualize that hole-in-one.

58:18.276 --> 58:22.154
Tell me. When you get to the altar,
do you spike the bouquet?

58:22.238 --> 58:25.240
- Okay, you know what--
- Well, I'm off.

58:25.324 --> 58:27.826
A reporter's work
is never done.

58:27.909 --> 58:29.827
See you later.
Bye, Mrs. Pressman. Thank you.

58:29.911 --> 58:34.164
I'm gonna go focus
on your eggs, Bob.

58:35.666 --> 58:38.126
I'm glad you're here.
I wanted to try to explain.

58:38.210 --> 58:42.421
There are reasons why there have been
three weddings and no "I do's."

58:42.463 --> 58:45.966
You can't believe how much cake
we got stuck with!

58:46.049 --> 58:48.260
It's a wonder
I don't weigh 300 pounds!

58:48.301 --> 58:51.179
And then, her father bought
all that booze that nobody drank.

58:51.262 --> 58:53.180
- But he didn't mind that--
- Hi, Grandma.

58:53.264 --> 58:55.349
[Makes Kissing Sound]
Hi, Netta.

58:55.432 --> 59:00.186
Grammy is giving me the skinny
on why you run from marital bliss.

59:00.270 --> 59:02.688
Right. Netta,
cover up your ears.

59:04.398 --> 59:06.525
It's not that she's afraid
of the wedding.

59:06.608 --> 59:09.819
- She's afraid of the wedding night!
- Mmm.

59:09.903 --> 59:13.406
Innocent girls are terrified
of the one-eyed snake.

59:15.950 --> 59:17.993
Why, when I was a virgin bride,

59:18.076 --> 59:20.328
I took a knitting needle
to bed with me.

59:20.412 --> 59:22.121
Uh--
[Clears Throat]

59:22.163 --> 59:24.498
Grandma, I charmed...

59:24.582 --> 59:29.336
- the one-eyed snake a while ago.
- Oh, yeah. I forgot.

59:29.419 --> 59:33.840
Well, I'll tell you one thing. Your
grandpa never forgot that wedding night.

59:33.923 --> 59:35.841
Netta, you can take
your hands down.

59:35.925 --> 59:37.843
- The tea's cold.
- Good.

59:37.926 --> 59:40.804
Could you excuse us for a minute?
May I have a word with you, please?

59:40.887 --> 59:43.973
Oh. Bye, Netta. Bye.

59:44.056 --> 59:46.850
Thanks, Grammy.

59:46.934 --> 59:49.353
Uh-- [Clears Throat]

59:49.436 --> 59:52.772
I found this, and I didn't know
if it was something interesting.

59:52.856 --> 59:56.275
- My-- This is Miles Davis!
- I was cleaning out the attic and--

59:56.358 --> 59:59.152
This is very hard to find
in good condition.

59:59.236 --> 01:00:03.656
- Hold on to this. This is incredible.
- Why don't you take it?

01:00:05.283 --> 01:00:08.410
- Huh?
- Take it.

01:00:08.494 --> 01:00:13.581
You're figuring out what kind of music
I like, finding me a rare album.

01:00:13.665 --> 01:00:16.542
You're not trying
to butter me up, are you?

01:00:16.625 --> 01:00:18.877
I was cleaning out the attic,

01:00:18.961 --> 01:00:22.672
not attempting the impossible.

01:00:22.714 --> 01:00:26.175
I smell trouble.

01:00:26.384 --> 01:00:29.762
[Car Radio] This is Cory Flemming,
and I'll be featuring the music...

01:00:29.845 --> 01:00:33.807
of Denise and Da Nephews,
tomorrow morning on "Wake up with--"

01:00:33.890 --> 01:00:35.808
[Turns Radio Off]

01:00:35.892 --> 01:00:38.352
[Ike]
What do we got here?

01:00:42.022 --> 01:00:44.357
[Maggie]
Come on, big guy.

01:00:44.440 --> 01:00:46.359
Oh, on our feet.
Here we go.

01:00:46.442 --> 01:00:49.194
Let's go, let's go,
big guy. Yeah.

01:00:49.278 --> 01:00:52.406
I haven't had any fun
since you got your driver's license.

01:00:52.489 --> 01:00:56.534
Let me give you a tip. I haven't
been having a whole lot of fun either.

01:00:57.952 --> 01:01:00.371
Steady.

01:01:00.454 --> 01:01:03.206
- Good boy, Porthole.
- His name's Skipper, Dad.

01:01:03.290 --> 01:01:05.708
- I changed it.
- Ah. Okay, step.

01:01:05.750 --> 01:01:09.879
- [Groans] I'll be back later, Travis.
- [Scoffs]

01:01:09.962 --> 01:01:12.673
- That guy Travis really has a problem.
- Mmm.

01:01:12.756 --> 01:01:14.799
- I'll get--
- Here we are.

01:01:14.883 --> 01:01:17.885
Okay. Steady.

01:01:17.969 --> 01:01:20.346
You're gonna lean,
I'm gonna push.

01:01:20.429 --> 01:01:23.223
Good daughters
let their fathers pass out.

01:01:23.265 --> 01:01:26.226
Hey, Walter.
Right down there.

01:01:26.267 --> 01:01:28.561
I, I-- Please, please
don't write anything--

01:01:28.603 --> 01:01:31.605
Forget about it.
Don't even think about it.

01:01:42.948 --> 01:01:46.910
I'm just so tired
of this whole scene.

01:01:46.951 --> 01:01:51.205
Why don't you just let him
sleep it off here in the truck?

01:01:51.247 --> 01:01:54.082
Come for a ride with me,
come back for him later.

01:01:56.751 --> 01:01:58.669
Okay.

01:02:04.633 --> 01:02:07.177
[Female Singer]
% Today %

01:02:07.260 --> 01:02:11.347
% We took a walk up the street %

01:02:11.430 --> 01:02:15.100
% We picked a flower
and climbed the hill %

01:02:15.142 --> 01:02:18.603
[Maggie] He's been drinking more
and more since my mom passed away.

01:02:18.686 --> 01:02:21.605
[Ike] That's when you quit school
to come back here?

01:02:21.647 --> 01:02:25.484
Yeah. I had to come
run the store for my dad.

01:02:25.567 --> 01:02:29.529
[Ike] My dad had
a small printing business.

01:02:29.612 --> 01:02:32.781
He wanted me to become
a classical musician.

01:02:32.823 --> 01:02:35.200
My mother wanted me
to be a novelist.

01:02:36.910 --> 01:02:39.120
They were 0-for-two.

01:02:42.248 --> 01:02:44.249
More?

01:02:44.333 --> 01:02:48.628
So, l, uh--
I became a reporter.

01:02:51.047 --> 01:02:53.674
Not quite a novelist.
But as we all know,

01:02:53.757 --> 01:02:57.677
journalism is literature
in a hurry.

01:03:00.596 --> 01:03:05.309
% I never saw blue
like that before %

01:03:06.810 --> 01:03:09.771
% Across the sky %

01:03:09.854 --> 01:03:11.814
[Ike]
What? What is this?

01:03:11.898 --> 01:03:14.275
What kind of gas did you put
in here? Diesel?

01:03:14.316 --> 01:03:17.736
I don't know.
The pump closest to the car.

01:03:17.819 --> 01:03:19.738
- [Car Backfires]
- Whoa!

01:03:21.322 --> 01:03:24.658
This car takes unleaded.
Your filter is clogged.

01:03:24.742 --> 01:03:26.660
[Ike]
Can you fix it?

01:03:26.743 --> 01:03:29.329
- I'm gonna need to get some tools.
- Oh, good.

01:03:29.412 --> 01:03:31.331
Kind of isolated here.

01:03:31.414 --> 01:03:34.125
Yeah, it's nice.

01:03:34.208 --> 01:03:36.752
[Sighs]

01:03:36.835 --> 01:03:40.046
Well, if there's one thing
us New Yorkers know how to do,

01:03:40.130 --> 01:03:41.798
that's hail a cab.

01:03:41.881 --> 01:03:44.300
If there's no cab, we walk.

01:03:44.342 --> 01:03:48.428
Uh, well, if we saved
the battery here,

01:03:48.512 --> 01:03:50.764
there's a place just down the way.

01:03:50.847 --> 01:03:54.016
We country girls cut across the field.
It's quicker.

01:03:59.563 --> 01:04:01.648
Oh, be careful of snakes.

01:04:03.524 --> 01:04:05.860
- What?
- Snakes.

01:04:05.943 --> 01:04:07.861
I don't like snakes.

01:04:07.945 --> 01:04:10.572
Walk nice.
They won't get ya.

01:04:12.740 --> 01:04:15.826
Come on, come on, come on!

01:04:15.910 --> 01:04:19.204
What're you--
What're you doing? Snake dance?

01:04:19.246 --> 01:04:22.373
I'm scaring the snakes.

01:04:22.457 --> 01:04:26.710
- You're scaring me.
- [Chuckles] I'm scaring myself.

01:04:29.087 --> 01:04:33.007
Do you think there's
one right person for everybody?

01:04:33.091 --> 01:04:35.343
[Sighs]
No, but I think attraction...

01:04:35.384 --> 01:04:39.388
is too often mistaken
for rightness.

01:04:39.471 --> 01:04:42.974
Attraction is very misleading.

01:04:43.057 --> 01:04:45.393
- Yes, it is.
- Yeah.

01:04:45.434 --> 01:04:47.520
- And it doesn't mean anything.
- No.

01:04:47.561 --> 01:04:51.773
No, no.
It doesn't mean anything. It means--

01:05:00.864 --> 01:05:03.658
I, uh,

01:05:03.742 --> 01:05:06.410
suddenly forgot
how to climb a fence.

01:05:08.704 --> 01:05:11.581
- Tools.
- Tools. Yeah.

01:05:20.756 --> 01:05:25.468
- Lionel, do you have tools?
- Hey, Maggie!

01:05:25.551 --> 01:05:27.845
What're you gonna do?
Bust out of another wedding?

01:05:27.928 --> 01:05:30.097
[Ike Laughs]

01:05:30.180 --> 01:05:33.558
Sure are well-known around here.

01:05:33.725 --> 01:05:36.728
[Ike]
No, Fish, it's almost done. I swear.

01:05:36.811 --> 01:05:39.146
This story's taken
a very interesting turn.

01:05:39.188 --> 01:05:42.024
I've got one more interview
to do in New York. I'll see you later.

01:05:42.065 --> 01:05:44.734
[Male Singer]
% From my head to my heart %

01:05:44.818 --> 01:05:48.821
% Can't seem to find a way
They're so far apart %

01:05:48.904 --> 01:05:51.365
[Horns Honking]

01:05:51.407 --> 01:05:54.784
You could've told me that
you were fianc number three.

01:05:54.868 --> 01:05:56.828
And end up in the papers?

01:05:56.911 --> 01:06:00.497
I've been humiliated enough already
to last a lifetime. Thank you.

01:06:00.581 --> 01:06:03.041
I was traveling around,

01:06:03.083 --> 01:06:06.920
studying the reproductive
and migratory patterns of locusts...

01:06:07.003 --> 01:06:08.921
when Maggie met me.

01:06:09.005 --> 01:06:12.174
Tell me, George.
Why do you think she ran?

01:06:12.216 --> 01:06:15.093
Just like you said.
What did you call her? A man-eater?

01:06:15.176 --> 01:06:19.180
Devouring death goddess.
All right?

01:06:19.263 --> 01:06:21.932
That's what I said.
I don't think that's why she ran.

01:06:22.016 --> 01:06:23.433
Why do you think she ran?

01:06:23.517 --> 01:06:26.019
I don't know. I'm working on it.
I was on the wrong track.

01:06:26.102 --> 01:06:29.647
- Are you defending her?
- No, no.

01:06:29.730 --> 01:06:33.859
I call it like I see it.
I'm a journalist. I'm a truth-teller.

01:06:33.942 --> 01:06:36.111
- Unbelievable!
- What?

01:06:36.194 --> 01:06:38.946
She got to you, too,
like a moth to a flame.

01:06:39.030 --> 01:06:40.948
- Please!
-Join the club.

01:06:41.032 --> 01:06:43.909
- What are you talking about?
- You need this much more than I do.

01:06:43.951 --> 01:06:48.288
I am a journalist. I'm doing an article.
Look. See? I'm being paid.

01:06:48.371 --> 01:06:53.500
This will be published. A cover story.
You'll get the all facts in the article.

01:06:53.584 --> 01:06:56.545
Do you know what kind
of eggs she liked?

01:06:56.628 --> 01:07:00.590
Poached, same as me.

01:07:07.262 --> 01:07:09.389
[Car Alarm Beeping]

01:07:09.472 --> 01:07:12.141
[Fisher] An over priced apartment
and Chinese take-out.

01:07:12.224 --> 01:07:14.226
That's New York living.

01:07:14.268 --> 01:07:16.353
Fisher, don't forget
the fortune cookies.

01:07:16.436 --> 01:07:20.732
I already read the fortune.
You don't wanna know.

01:07:20.815 --> 01:07:23.776
He makes me crazy.

01:07:23.859 --> 01:07:26.945
Hostility is a very important part
of your foreplay, isn't it?

01:07:27.028 --> 01:07:29.822
It takes three people
to make our marriage work:

01:07:29.906 --> 01:07:31.741
him, me and our therapist.

01:07:34.076 --> 01:07:37.037
[Laughs]

01:07:37.120 --> 01:07:40.206
Ellie, what went wrong?

01:07:40.290 --> 01:07:43.209
With us.
With the two of us, I mean.

01:07:43.292 --> 01:07:48.797
I know it's been a long time.
Do you remember?

01:07:48.880 --> 01:07:52.800
Yeah. Do I remember?
Of course I do.

01:07:54.718 --> 01:07:57.971
Is that what--
Did I do the same--

01:07:58.013 --> 01:08:02.058
Is that what happened?
Did I just... not see you?

01:08:04.643 --> 01:08:08.438
No. No, you didn't.

01:08:14.693 --> 01:08:16.653
I'm sorry.

01:08:16.694 --> 01:08:19.156
I'm sorry, Ellie.

01:08:19.197 --> 01:08:21.282
I'm sorry too, Ike.

01:08:23.408 --> 01:08:27.037
Wow! That only took us
1 2 years to say.

01:08:27.121 --> 01:08:30.040
Hey, I saw that, you cad.

01:08:30.122 --> 01:08:33.126
You asked for it, you got it.
Here you go.

01:08:33.209 --> 01:08:35.127
My dear.

01:08:35.211 --> 01:08:37.671
Get your fortune.
Let me see what--

01:08:37.755 --> 01:08:42.884
"Confucius say, man who leave wife alone
with ex-husband may leave altogether."

01:08:42.966 --> 01:08:44.468
- [Laughing]
- Aha!

01:08:44.719 --> 01:08:47.763
- Lights and everything.
- Hope it's better than last year.

01:08:47.845 --> 01:08:49.890
[Woman Laughing]
Or the last ten years.

01:08:49.973 --> 01:08:53.059
%[Drums Beating]

01:08:53.142 --> 01:08:55.560
[Cheering, Whistling]

01:09:01.483 --> 01:09:02.984
[Applauding]

01:09:03.067 --> 01:09:06.694
Let's have a hand for
our fabulous hula dancers.

01:09:06.737 --> 01:09:11.825
There they are.
King and Queen!

01:09:11.908 --> 01:09:14.911
% [Hawaiian]

01:09:14.993 --> 01:09:19.915
Walter, I'm thinking about
going back to my maiden name.

01:09:19.997 --> 01:09:21.917
Can you still remember it?

01:09:22.000 --> 01:09:25.502
What? It's nice, you know.

01:09:25.545 --> 01:09:30.966
It's just I haven't seen him
in 24 hours, and I would...

01:09:31.049 --> 01:09:35.011
feel better if
I knew where he was, you see.

01:09:38.555 --> 01:09:41.265
[Mr. Trout]
Welcome to our annual luau.

01:09:41.350 --> 01:09:44.269
- What can I get you?
- [Ike] Aloha, Mr. Trout.

01:09:44.352 --> 01:09:48.856
Uh, you got something
without a toy in it?

01:09:48.939 --> 01:09:51.316
% [Electric Guitar]

01:09:51.399 --> 01:09:54.319
- [Man] Get down, Sprout.
- The next three.

01:09:54.402 --> 01:09:56.362
Yeah.

01:09:56.446 --> 01:09:59.740
Oh, I'm hearing it here.

01:10:03.910 --> 01:10:05.828
Aloha!

01:10:08.122 --> 01:10:10.582
It's a very fetching headdress
you're wearing.

01:10:14.419 --> 01:10:18.589
Where did--
Where did you disappear to?

01:10:18.673 --> 01:10:20.633
Missed me bad, huh?

01:10:23.760 --> 01:10:25.887
[Betty Trout]
And we have a winner right here!

01:10:25.970 --> 01:10:29.140
Yeah! All right, Bob!

01:10:29.223 --> 01:10:32.684
Well, it's chow time
here on the islands,

01:10:32.768 --> 01:10:37.063
and we Trouts have prepared
our traditional feast, Shrimp Trout.

01:10:37.146 --> 01:10:39.440
So let's all meet at the tables.

01:10:39.482 --> 01:10:41.650
You're not allergic
to shrimp, are you?

01:10:41.734 --> 01:10:44.903
- Mmm, no.
- Pity.

01:10:45.987 --> 01:10:48.531
[Banging]

01:10:50.616 --> 01:10:54.077
Attention!
Pay attention to Walter.

01:10:54.161 --> 01:10:57.080
- Listen closely. He slurs.
- [Laughing]

01:10:57.163 --> 01:10:59.874
In the tradition...

01:10:59.957 --> 01:11:03.418
that has grown over the years,
it is now toast time.

01:11:03.460 --> 01:11:05.587
First up, our host,

01:11:05.629 --> 01:11:08.339
Lou "A Honey of a Beekeeper" Trout.

01:11:08.423 --> 01:11:10.758
[Applause]

01:11:10.800 --> 01:11:12.801
[Whistles]

